INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '79ee54fc-e154-496f-b8a3-5eb3a27b5180',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Turbopack Source Maps — Types, Trade-offs, and What to Ship in Production$escape$,
  $escape$Turbopack generates source maps incrementally — only reprocessing changed modules — so high-fidelity maps add minimal overhead during development. Production is a different calculus.

Next.js exposes a single toggle for shipping maps to the browser: `productionBrowserSourceMaps: true` in `next.config.ts`. With this enabled, `.map` files are emitted alongside JS bundles and referenced via `//# sourceMappingURL`. Anyone with DevTools can read your original source. For internal tooling, that's acceptable. For competitive or IP-sensitive products, it's a liability.

The safer pattern: generate maps, upload them to your error tracker, then exclude them from your CDN deploy. `@sentry/nextjs` handles this via `withSentryConfig` — it uploads maps to Sentry's API then deletes them post-build. Note: Turbopack plugin support in `withSentryConfig` is still rolling out as of Next.js 15.3, so verify your Sentry SDK version supports it.

Unlike webpack, Turbopack doesn't expose a `devtool` enum (`cheap-module-source-map`, `eval-source-map`, etc.). Source map fidelity is controlled at the Next.js config level, not per-loader. This removes the escape hatch of trading map quality for build speed — but Turbopack's Rust core makes that trade-off largely irrelevant in dev anyway.$escape$,
  $escape$// next.config.ts
import type { NextConfig } from 'next'
import { withSentryConfig } from '@sentry/nextjs'

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  // Emit .map files — required for upload; strip before CDN
  productionBrowserSourceMaps: true,
}

export default withSentryConfig(nextConfig, {
  org: 'your-org',
  project: 'your-project',
  sourcemaps: {
    deleteSourcemapsAfterUpload: true,
  },
})$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
