INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6bfea052-4825-421d-a354-efed8fc03b2a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Turbopack — Transpile-Only vs Type-Checking: The Speed-Safety Trade-Off$escape$,
  $escape$Turbopack, like esbuild before it, strips TypeScript types at build time without running `tsc`. This is transpile-only mode — it removes annotations and emits JS at near-instant speeds, but never catches type errors. In Next.js 15+ with Turbopack as the default dev bundler, this is exactly what happens: `next dev --turbo` gives you sub-100ms HMR because type-checking is simply not part of the pipeline.

The implication: a component can have `string` where you meant `number`, and Turbopack will happily bundle and serve it. Your dev server stays fast; your runtime blows up.

The pragmatic fix is a parallel type-check process. Run `tsc --noEmit --watch` in a second terminal alongside `next dev --turbo`. You get Turbopack's speed for bundling and incremental React updates, while tsc catches contract violations independently. In CI, gate merges on `tsc --noEmit` — never on the Turbopack build output itself. This two-track model is the production-safe pattern: Turbopack owns speed, tsc owns correctness.$escape$,
  $escape$// package.json — two-track dev workflow
{
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "next dev --turbo",
    "typecheck": "tsc --noEmit --watch",
    "dev:safe": "concurrently 'next dev --turbo' 'tsc --noEmit --watch'",
    "build": "tsc --noEmit && next build"
  }
}

// next.config.ts — Turbopack config (does not add type-checking)
export default {
  experimental: {
    turbo: {
      resolveAlias: {}
    }
  }
} satisfies import('next').NextConfig;$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
