INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '99db9978-621f-405a-a94e-d1c55d9f27d2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Turbopack — Build Time Tracking and Bundle Size Regression Alerts in CI$escape$,
  $escape$Turbopack exposes build metrics via `--log-level verbose` and structured JSON output when running `next build` with the `TURBOPACK=1` flag. Capture these in CI by piping stdout to a parser that extracts the `compileTime` and per-chunk `size` fields from Turbopack's trace output.

Store baseline metrics as a CI artifact on your main branch. On each PR, compare the new build output against the baseline using a threshold script — flag any chunk exceeding a 10% size increase or build time regression beyond 15 seconds. Turbopack's module graph is deterministic per cache state, so size regressions almost always point to an unintended import or a missing tree-shake boundary.

Use `NEXT_TURBOPACK_TRACING=1` to emit `.trace` files compatible with Perfetto. These files break down time by transform, resolve, and chunk phases — critical for pinpointing which module is bloating your compile time. Pair this with GitHub Actions' `actions/upload-artifact` to persist traces per PR for async review.$escape$,
  $escape$# .github/workflows/bundle-check.yml
- name: Build with Turbopack tracing
  env:
    TURBOPACK: 1
    NEXT_TURBOPACK_TRACING: 1
  run: next build 2>&1 | tee build-output.txt

- name: Check bundle size regression
  run: |
    node scripts/check-bundle-size.mjs \
      --baseline .bundle-baseline.json \
      --current build-output.txt \
      --threshold 10

- name: Upload Turbopack trace
  uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
  with:
    name: turbopack-trace-${{ github.sha }}
    path: .next/trace$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
